{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520730"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:28:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:28:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13435"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13435"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.37,0.04,0.35,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6047"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79785"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6047"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13435"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65093"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11054"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11517"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15209"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43419"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79785"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old female presents to her respiratory physician whom she has been visiting for the past 1 year, seeking additional treatment options for her asthma because of frequent exacerbations and nocturnal symptoms impacting her daily activities despite allergen avoidance and being compliant on high-dose inhaled corticosteroids (ICS), long-acting beta-agonists (LABA) and long-acting muscarinic antagonists (LAMA) for the past 1-2 years. Of note, she has also had multiple courses of oral corticosteroids in the last 12 months. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EOn physical examination, her vitals are Blood pressure: 138/94, pulse: 99, respiratory rate: 20/min, temperature. 37C, respiratory exam reveals mild end-expiratory wheezing and a prolonged expiratory phase. Her lab results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHb: 131 g/L (125 \u2013 160)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWBCs: 9.4 (4.0 \u2013 11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils: 6.4 (1.8 - 7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEosinophils: 0.09 (0.02 - 0.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal serum IgE: 130 IU/mL (\u003C100 IU/ml)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following therapies should this patient be considered for?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dupilumab","Montelukast","Benralizumab","Omalizumab","Allergen immunotherapy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in this scenario has presented with severe asthma despite triple therapy and allergen avoidance. \u003Cstrong\u003EOmalizumab\u003C/strong\u003E, a monoclonal antibody targeting immunoglobulin E (IgE), is the appropriate therapy for this patient. Omalizumab binds to free IgE, preventing its interaction with mast cells and basophils, thereby reducing the release of inflammatory mediators in response to allergen exposure. Indications for omalizumab therapy include elevated serum total IgE level \u003E30IU/mL despite at least 12 months of appropriate asthma therapy, including with an inhaled corticosteroid. As well, the patient must be known to the respiratory physician for a minimum of six months and definitive proof of asthma on pulmonary function tests. Of note, part of the Omalizumab criteria also requires treatment with oral corticosteroids for at least 6 weeks or a cumulative dose of \u003E500mg within 12 months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDupilumab\u003C/strong\u003E, a monoclonal antibody targeting the interleukin-4 receptor alpha subunit, is indicated for the treatment of moderate-to-severe asthma with eosinophilic phenotype. However, in this patient, the eosinophil levels are within the normal range, suggesting a non-eosinophilic asthma phenotype. Therefore, dupilumab may not be the most appropriate therapy in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMontelukast\u003C/strong\u003E, a leukotriene receptor antagonist, is commonly used as an adjunctive therapy for asthma. However, its efficacy in severe, uncontrolled asthma, particularly in patients already on high-dose ICS, LABA, and oral corticosteroids, is limited.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenralizumab\u003C/strong\u003E, an anti-interleukin-5 receptor alpha monoclonal antibody, is indicated for severe eosinophilic asthma inadequately controlled by high-dose ICS and other asthma controllers, such as LABA. Given the absence of elevated eosinophil levels in this patient, benralizumab may not effectively target the underlying pathophysiology of her asthma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllergen immunotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is a treatment option for allergic asthma aimed at modifying the immune response to allergens. However, in this patient with uncontrolled asthma despite maximal therapy and the absence of a significant allergic component in her clinical presentation, allergen immunotherapy is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A patient with severe uncontrolled asthma with elevated IgE levels of \u003E30IU/mL is a candidate for omalizumab therapy.","Patients must have been treated with oral corticosteroids for at least 6 weeks or received a cumulative dose of \u003E500mg within 12 months to qualify for omalizumab.","Patients must be known to a respiratory physician for at least 6 months before commencing omalizumab therapy."],"references":["Shah PA, Brightling C. Biologics for severe asthma-Which, when and why?. Respirology. 2023;28(8):709-721. doi:10.1111/resp.14520","Yoo J, Meyers J, Reddel H. Difficult-to-treat and severe asthma in adults: Towards a new treatment paradigm. Aust J Gen Pract. 2019;48(4):188-192. doi:10.31128/AJGP-10-18-4750"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65093"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13435"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65093"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T19:25:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T19:28:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6047"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79785"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"h